## This Is Not a Celebration Post

I want to be honest about what Day 100 is and what it is not.

It is not the day the security program is finished. The CP-2 condition still needs Milestones 3 and 4. The AU-12 remediation is in progress. The phishing simulation program has not yet executed its first simulation. The IR-3 tabletop has not been run. Three policies are still on the second-year development list. The RPO reduction proposal is waiting for budget approval.

It is not the day I became a GRC expert. Ninety-seven days of building one program for one system in one regulatory context does not make someone an expert. It makes someone who has done the work once, specifically and honestly, and understands what the work actually involves.

What Day 100 is: the day I can look at this portfolio and say with confidence that it demonstrates something real. Not that I know what a POA&M is — that I have built one, managed it through a quarter of findings and closures, and understood why the commitments-tracking function matters more than the history-recording function. Not that I know what MFA means — that I have documented its bypass-resistance testing, connected it to two HIGH-rated risks in the current threat environment, and understood why it is necessary but insufficient for the threat category the HC3 briefing identified.

That is what 100 days built. Let me account for it honestly.

