## What This Project Is in a Job Interview

I want to be direct about this because it is part of why this project exists.

When a hiring manager asks "can you describe a GRC project you have worked on?" the answer this portfolio supports is not "I completed a 100-day challenge where I learned GRC concepts." The answer is:

"I built a complete RMF-aligned GRC program for an open-source electronic health record system deployed on AWS for a healthcare NGO. The system stores ePHI for HIV/AIDS and mental health patients — a population where unauthorized disclosure causes social harm beyond standard HIPAA breach metrics, which drove a HIGH categorization across all three security objectives.

The program went through the full NIST RMF cycle: FIPS 199 categorization, HIGH baseline control selection with tailoring, full SSP development, formal assessment producing twelve findings, conditional ATO with four conditions, and eight months of continuous monitoring. The monitoring program identified four findings that the formal assessment did not, including a Moderate-severity AU-12 gap I found through a semi-annual self-assessment that automated monitoring had not detected.

The capstone synthesized the full program into a nine-section authorization package with current-state compliance mapping, evolved risk register, control effectiveness analysis, policy architecture, training program with phishing simulation design, incident response playbooks including a pre-authorized EC2 isolation procedure, and a complete POA&M with aging analysis.

The most important thing I learned is the difference between present controls and effective controls — and why the monitoring program exists to close that gap continuously."

That answer is specific. It names real findings. It describes real judgments. It demonstrates the kind of operational depth that framework knowledge alone cannot produce.

