## What I Would Tell Someone Starting This Journey

After 100 days, the advice I would give someone starting Day 1 has nothing to do with frameworks or tools. It is this:

**Pick a real system and stay with it.** The learning happens through specificity. The moment you have to decide whether the FIPS 199 confidentiality impact is HIGH or MODERATE for THIS system storing THESE records for THESE patients, you develop an analytical capability that no generic answer can produce. Every vague answer you allow yourself to give is a missed learning opportunity.

**Find the gaps honestly.** The most valuable security documentation in this project was not the documentation that showed the controls working — it was the AU-12 finding documented with a note to assessors, the CP-2 AT RISK status communicated with a specific ask, the POA&M items that named process compliance failures as organizational culture problems rather than individual mistakes. Honest documentation is not vulnerability — it is maturity.

**Connect every control to the people it protects.** The encryption controls protect HIV status records. The audit logging protects patients whose access misuse might not be reported. The contingency plan protects antiretroviral therapy patients who depend on continuous medication records. When you understand who benefits from the security work, the compliance motivation becomes secondary to the genuine purpose.

**Learn one real breach per major concept.** The Target breach for access review accuracy. The Anthem breach for human-layer training investment. The Premera case for POA&M accountability. The URMC settlement for compliance mapping traceability. Real cases do more conceptual work than any number of framework descriptions because they connect the abstract to the consequential.

**Treat communication as a security control.** The ISSO who cannot communicate the CP-2 AT RISK status in a way that produces AO action has failed at security governance regardless of how accurate the documentation is. The communication artifacts developed in Days 85 and 96 are as much a part of the security program as the technical controls. Decision-support communication is the final layer of every security control chain.

